answers.body_markdown:
The integer array gameState is initialized with default values.
The onSaveInstanceState method saves the array to the Bundle with the key &quot;gameState&quot;.
The onRestoreInstanceState method restores the array from the Bundle.
The above example should be enough to persist the gameState across activity destruction and re-creation  due to screen rotation).

    public class MainActivity extends AppCompatActivity {

    int[] gameState = {2, 2, 2, 2, 2, 2, 2, 2, 2};

    @Override
    protected void onCreate(Bundle savedInstanceState) {
        super.onCreate(savedInstanceState);
        setContentView(R.layout.activity_main);
        
        if (savedInstanceState != null) {
            gameState = savedInstanceState.getIntArray(&quot;gameState&quot;);
        }
    }

    @Override
    protected void onSaveInstanceState(Bundle outState) {
        super.onSaveInstanceState(outState);
        outState.putIntArray(&quot;gameState&quot;, gameState);
    }

    @Override
    protected void onRestoreInstanceState(Bundle savedInstanceState) {
        super.onRestoreInstanceState(savedInstanceState);
        gameState = savedInstanceState.getIntArray(&quot;gameState&quot;);
    }
}


As you&#39;re dealing with screen rotation, it might be helpful to handle the restoration of the game state in onCreate as well, just in case onRestoreInstanceState is not called. As you can see in the example, the gameState is checked and possibly restored in onCreate.

